The project aims to study low surface brightness emission with large angular extent, so we request night time observations avoiding sunrise and sunset to reduce solar interference on short baselines, as specified in the proposal.

Following https://skaafrica.atlassian.net/servicedesk/customer/portal/1/topic/c963d622-de70-4f24-95cb-657cc5962d78/article/899448833, we split the observation into a rising and a setting tracks to expedite scheduling. This increased the overheads from the estimated 25% to ~30%. Following the same link, we considered this acceptable in the cause of reducing scheduling idle time.

column2: A Pilot Study to Measure Magnetic Fields of Solar Corona and Coronal Mass Ejections using Faraday Rotation Observations using MeerKAT
column25: The preferred dates are the 22nd and 23rd of December for the first set of observations. Since the pointings change with date (calculated at certain distances from the Sun and Sun changes its RA by ~1deg/day), these given pointings are only valid over 1-2 days. We chose these dates because the Parker Solar Probe will be in the same location to do in-situ measurements of solar wind and coronal mass ejections. Hence, observing at the same time is scientifically advantageous. This 3-hour observation will be used to demonstrate the feasibility as suggested by the technical reviewer.

In our proposal (7h on target time at priority A) we requested night-time observations, avoiding sunrise/sunset and single track observation to maximize the uv-coverage. However, to facilitate a more efficient scheduling, we decided to split the observation in half, with one rising schedule, and a setting schedule (this one). The time on target is 3.5h for each schedule. We included preferred dates for this setting track. Until 15/01/2025 and between the dates 01/11/2025 - 31/12/2025 the starting LST range should be 03:00 - 04:50. These dates and starting LST ranges are selected to avoid sunrise/sunset, observe during the night-time and for a setting track schedule, as strongly motivated in our accepted MeerKAT proposal. The other identical schedule we submitted is for a rising track.
